ntra: A Critical Edition of the Leaves Contained in Cambridge University Library Or.158.1 -- tMahā-Daṇḍadhāraṇī-Śītavatī: A Buddhist Apotropaic Scripture -- tMinor Vajrayāna Texts IV. A Sanskrit fragment of the Rigyarallitantra -- tWhen Lachmann's Method Meets the Dharma of Śiva. Common Errors, Scribal Interventions, and the Transmission of the Śivadharma Corpus -- tCultural Studies -- tVivid Images, Not Opaque Words -- tUmā and Śiva's Playful Talks in Detail (Lalitavistara): On the Production of Śaiva Works and their Manuscripts in Medieval Nepal -- tSubantaratnākara: An Unknown Text of Subhūticandra -- tThe Cāndravyākaraṇapañjikā: An Important Tool for the Study of the Moggallānavuttivivaraṇapañcikā -- tTowards a Critical Edition of Śaṅkara's 'Longer' Aitareyopaniṣadbhāṣya: a Preliminary Report based on two Cambridge Manuscripts -- tList of Contributors -- tIndex of Persons0 aOpen Accessuhttps://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_abf2funrestricted online access2star  aThis collection of essays explores the history of the book in pre-modern South Asia looking at the production, circulation, fruition and preservation of manuscripts in different areas and across time. Edited by the team of the Cambridge-based Sanskrit Manuscripts Project and including contributions of the researchers who collaborated with it, it covers a wide range of topics related to South Asian manuscript culture: from the material dimension (palaeography, layout, decoration) and the complicated interactions of manuscripts with printing in late medieval Tibet and in modern Tamil Nadu, to reading, writing, editing and educational practices, from manuscripts as sources for the study of religious, literary and intellectual traditions, to the creation of collections in medieval India and Cambodia (one major centre of the so-called Sanskrit cosmopolis), and the formation of the Cambridge collections in the colonial period. The contributions reflect the variety of idioms, literary genres, religious movements, and social actors (intellectuals, scribes, patrons) of ancient South Asia, as well as the variety of approaches, interests and specialisms of the authors, and their impassionate engagement with manuscripts.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nd/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aManuscriptszSouth AsiaxHistory. 0aManuscripts, IndicxHistory. 0aManuscripts, IndiczEnglandzCambridgexHistory. 0aManuscripts, SanskritxHistory. 0aManuscripts, SanskritzEnglandzCambridgexHistory. 4aIndien. 4aManuskript. 4aSanskrit. 4aSüdasien. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Books & Reading.2bisacsh  aCambridge manuscript collections.  aIndian Manuscript Culture.  aSouth Asia.1 aBalbir, Nalini, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCiotti, Giovanni, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClemente, Michela, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCuneo, Daniele, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCuneo, Daniele, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDavid, Hugo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDe Simini, Florinda, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDeokar, Lata Mahesh, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDeokar, Mahesh A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFormigatti, Camillo A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFormigatti, Camillo Alessio, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aFranceschini, Marco, econtribut